Hereâ€™s a simple explanationÂ of the types of memory in Java:



ï¿½ï¿½ 1. Heap Memory
Â·Â 
Used for: Objects and instance variables
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Allocated at runtime using newÂ keyword.
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Managed by Garbage CollectorÂ (frees memory automatically).
Â·Â 
Student s = new Student(); // Stored in heap
âœ… Big memory area, shared among all threads.



ï¿½ï¿½ 2. Stack Memory
Â·Â 
Used for: Method calls, local variables
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Follows LIFOÂ (Last-In-First-Out).
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Each thread has its own stack.
Â·Â 
void greet() {
Â Â Â Â int x = 10; // x is stored in stack
}
âœ… Fast but limited in size.



ï¿½ï¿½ 3. Method Area (MetaSpace in Java 8+)
Â·Â 
Stores: Class-level data, like:
Â·Â 
oÂ 
Class definitions
oÂ 
oÂ 
Static variables
oÂ 
oÂ 
Method code (bytecode)
oÂ 
âœ… Shared among all classes.



ï¿½ï¿½ 4. Program Counter (PC) Register
Â·Â 
Each thread has its own PC register.
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Keeps track of the current instructionÂ being executed.
Â·Â 
âœ… Small memory block, used internally by JVM.



ï¿½ï¿½ 5. Native Method Stack
Â·Â 
Used when Java code calls native (C/C++) codeÂ using JNI (Java Native Interface).
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Stores native method information.
Â·Â 



âœ… Summary Table:
Memory Type	Stores	Scope
Heap	Objects, instance variables	Shared
Stack	Local variables, method calls	Per thread
Method Area	Class info, static variables, bytecode	Shared
PC Register	Current executing instruction	Per thread
Native Method Stack	Native code info	Per thread


