16. Why Is String Immutable in Java?
Strings in Java are immutable, meaning that once aÂ StringÂ object is created, its content cannot be changed.Â Any operation that appears to modify aÂ StringÂ actually results in the creation of a newÂ StringÂ object with the altered content.Â This design choice offers several significant advantages:Â 
ï¿½ï¿½ Reasons:
Â·Â 
Security:Â Used in ClassLoader, URL, etc.
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
Thread-safety:Â Can be shared across threads without sync.
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
HashCode caching:Â Ideal for keys in HashMap.
Â·Â 
Â·Â 
ClassLoader behavior:Â Prevents hacking via reflection.
Â·Â 
String s = "Hello";
s.concat("World"); Â // Original string not modified
System.out.println(s); Â // Outputs: Hello



17. ==Â vs .equals()Â in String
Comparison	Purpose	Compares
==	Reference check	Memory address
.equals()	Value/content check	Actual string value

String str1 = "hello";
String str2 = "hello";
String str3 = new String("hello");

// Using == to compare references
boolean result1 = str1 == str2;  // true, because they refer to the same instance in the string pool
boolean result2 = str1 == str3;  // false, because str3 is a new object with a different memory address

String str1 = "hello";
String str2 = "hello";
String str3 = new String("hello");

// Using .equals() to compare content of strings
boolean result1 = str1.equals(str2);  // true, because their contents are the same
boolean result2 = str1.equals(str3);  // true, even though str3 is a different object



