17. Difference Between yield()Â and sleep()
Hereâ€™s a clear and simple difference between yield() and sleep() in Java:

âœ… 1. yield()
* Purpose: Suggests to the Thread Scheduler that the current thread is willing to pause to let other threads of the same priority run.
* Does NOT block the thread â€” just a hint, not guaranteed.
* The thread can be rescheduled immediately.
ğŸ§  Real-Life Analogy:â€¨Youâ€™re at a coffee machine and say, "Anyone want to go first?" If no one does, you continue.

âœ… 2. sleep()
* Purpose: Forces the thread to pause execution for a specific time (in milliseconds or nanoseconds).
* The thread definitely stops and enters the TIMED_WAITING state.
* The thread wonâ€™t run again until the sleep time is over, even if the CPU is free.
ğŸ§  Real-Life Analogy:â€¨You take a nap for 5 minutes. Youâ€™re not getting up before the alarm.

ğŸ”¸ Comparison Table
Feature	yield()	sleep()
Purpose	Suggest to pause voluntarily	Forcefully pause for fixed time
Time Control	No â€” resumes immediately if chosen	Yes â€” pauses for specified time
Guarantees Pause?	No â€” only a hint	Yes â€” always pauses
Thread State	Ready-to-run	TIMED_WAITING
InterruptedException	Not thrown	Can throw InterruptedException


18. How to Implement Thread-Safe Singleton?
public class Singleton {
Â Â Â Â private static volatile Singleton instance;
Â 
Â Â Â Â private Singleton() {}
Â 
Â Â Â Â public static Singleton getInstance() {
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â if (instance == null) {
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â synchronized(Singleton.class) {
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â if (instance == null) {
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â instance = new Singleton();
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â }
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â }
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â }
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â return instance;
Â Â Â Â }
}
âœ… Uses Double-Checked LockingÂ + volatileÂ for thread-safety.



19. When to Use volatileÂ Over synchronized?
